<DOC><DOCNO> AP890926-0244 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-09-26-89 0753EDT</FILEID><FIRST>d f BC-Janeway     09-26 0111</FIRST><SECOND>BC-Janeway,0117</SECOND><HEAD>One-Time FDR Adviser Urges Drug Legalization</HEAD><DATELINE>DEARBORN, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Economist Eliot Janeway, an adviser toPresident Franklin Roosevelt, says the United States should givedrugs away to cut crime and illicit drug profits.   ``Let's fall back on an ancient, honorable, all-Americanpreference for getting something for nothing. Let's make users andaddicts an offer they can't resist,'' Janeway, 76, told the DetroitEconomic Club on Monday.   ``Activate the U.S. government for a business it knows and doesbest: handouts,'' Janeway said, describing efforts to fight drugsas a ``fruitless operation.''   Janeway said hard-line drug policies merely swell prisonpopulations and result in more young, poor, urban dealers.</TEXT></DOC>